{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5d568003-a237-452a-8625-af64bffff33f","content":"This is a known **breaking change** caused by C# 14's updated overload resolution for span types.\n\n## What happened\n\nIn C# 13, arrays gained implicit conversions to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. In C# 14, overload resolution was updated to **prefer span-based overloads**, so:\n\n- **.NET 9:** `array.Contains(num)` resolves to **`Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`**\n- **.NET 10:** it now resolves to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`**\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it cannot be represented in expression trees. The expression tree interpreter blows up at runtime when it hits the span-based method call.\n\n## How to fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the LINQ overload. Either cast the receiver or call the method explicitly:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: cast to IEnumerable<int>\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n\n// Option 2: call Enumerable.Contains directly (static syntax)\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth force the compiler back to `Enumerable.Contains<T>`, which is expression-tree-safe. The same pattern applies to other `MemoryExtensions` methods (e.g., `IndexOf`, `SequenceEqual`) that now win overload resolution on arrays.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"88b0dee9-d1b3-4eac-bf69-40d69b21eeaa","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to **extension members** and how the compiler resolves extension methods. Specifically, C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's a change in how `Enumerable.Contains()` vs `MemoryExtensions.Contains()` is resolved.\n\n\nThe key difference is that in .NET 10, the compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains()` for `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` over the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains()` method, which changes how arrays are handled since arrays can be implicitly converted to spans. Since arrays are implicitly convertible to `Span<T>` in newer C# versions, the compiler might now prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains()` over `Enumerable.Contains()`.\n\nWait, actually this is a known breaking change. In .NET 9 / C# 13, arrays became implicitly convertible to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and `MemoryExtensions.Contains(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` became a candidate. But in C# 13, extension method resolution still preferred `Enumerable.Contains` because the implicit span conversion wasn't preferred over the interface conversion.\n\nActually, I think the specific issue is: in C# 14, the compiler now resolves `array.Contains(value)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` due to changes in overload resolution with span types.\n\nThe real problem is that expression trees can't represent calls involving `Span<T>` or `ReadOnlySpan<T>` since spans are ref structs and can't be boxed or used in expression trees. So when the compiler tries to build an expression tree for a lambda that calls `.Contains()` on an array, it fails at compile time because it can't express the span-based method call.\n\nBut the user says it throws at runtime, not compile time. So maybe the expression tree is being built dynamically at runtime, or maybe I'm misunderstanding when the resolution happens.\n\nLet me reconsider this from a different angle. The issue might be related to overload resolution changes between C# 13 and C# 14, particularly around how implicit conversions from arrays to spans work with methods like `Contains`. In C# 13, implicit array-to-span conversions were added, which could have changed which overload gets selected at compile time, and that selected overload might not be compatible with expression trees when evaluated at runtime. span, T value)` became a viable candidate for `array.Contains(value)`. However, in C# 13, the extension method resolution still preferred `Enumerable.Contains` in most cases.\n\nBut in C# 14, the overload resolution rules may have changed such that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` is now preferred over `Enumerable.Contains` for array receivers.\n\nThe key issue: `MemoryExtensions.Contains` takes a `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter (a ref struct). Expression trees cannot represent ref structs. So if the compiler tries to build an expression tree with a call to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, it should fail at compile time with CS8640 or similar.\n\nBut the user's code uses a lambda assigned to `Expression<Func<...>>`, which is compile-time. So it should fail at compile time, unless the compiler still compiles it but the generated expression tree has issues at runtime. Actually, I think the answer might be simpler—in C# 14, the compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` and refuses to compile the expression tree entirely. The user might be describing it as a runtime error because they're building the expression tree manually or using a library that constructs it dynamically, or they simplified their code for the question. The real technical answer is that in C# 14 / .NET 10, overload resolution now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` for array receivers, which breaks expression tree compilation.\n\nThe fix is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the older overload resolution path.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering whether this is actually a compile-time or runtime error—the user says it throws at runtime, but given the code shown, C# 14 should catch this at compile time since ref structs can't be used in expression trees. The most likely explanation is that they're building expression trees dynamically or working with pre-compiled code, but either way, the root cause is the same: overload resolution is picking `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. Contains()` on arrays in the .NET 9/10 timeframe is the span overload resolution change. The root cause is that C# 14 updated overload resolution so `array.Contains(value)` now prefers `System.MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`, since implicit array-to-span conversions are now prioritized. This breaks in expression trees because ref structs like `ReadOnlySpan<T>` aren't allowed in expression tree contexts.\n\nThe fix is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the older overload resolution path.","outputTokens":2921},"id":"f57cce0f-357d-4b73-a887-1fe9b05fbee1","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:34:01.593Z","parentId":"b2d510af-fd56-4f6e-b13d-d7627a86a6c1"}
